00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:39.140
JOSE DOMINGUEZ-CABALLERO: OK.

00:00:39.140 --> 00:00:42.320
Can we-- so today,
the goal today

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:46.520
is to show you a couple of
very interesting experiments.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:48.230
And again, the idea
of this is for you

00:00:48.230 --> 00:00:53.600
to see all these derivations
that we've been doing actually

00:00:53.600 --> 00:00:55.730
applied in a real experiment
and see the results

00:00:55.730 --> 00:00:56.690
that you would expect.

00:00:56.690 --> 00:00:59.450
And for instance, these
last [? pieces, ?]

00:00:59.450 --> 00:01:02.960
you were supposed to compute the
interference between a couple--

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:05.570
two plane waves propagating
at a different angle,

00:01:05.570 --> 00:01:08.730
so you were supposed
to also calculate

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:09.950
analytical solution of that.

00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:13.140
Now, we're going to see the
real evidence of that solution.

00:01:13.140 --> 00:01:15.980
So for that, we actually built,
in this case, a little more

00:01:15.980 --> 00:01:19.490
elaborate setup than the ones
that we've been showing before.

00:01:19.490 --> 00:01:22.500
This actually a
Mach-Zehnder interferometer

00:01:22.500 --> 00:01:26.210
that Professor Sheppard
described last time,

00:01:26.210 --> 00:01:28.640
and I will explain
it very briefly.

00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:31.770
Can we zoom out, please?

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:34.270
Controls?

00:01:34.270 --> 00:01:36.620
I guess maybe
that's the maximum.

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:38.440
All right, so we start
here with a laser.

00:01:41.553 --> 00:01:42.970
So the laser comes
from this side,

00:01:42.970 --> 00:01:46.970
and up to this section
here is where we just

00:01:46.970 --> 00:01:49.960
collimate the
light, so basically,

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:52.780
what I'm going to focus right
now is on this other section.

00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:56.020
So after this part here,
we have a nice plane wave.

00:01:56.020 --> 00:01:57.765
This component
here is a polarizer

00:01:57.765 --> 00:02:00.340
that, right now, just
take it as an element that

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:03.490
allows me to control
the intensity such

00:02:03.490 --> 00:02:07.090
that the CCD doesn't
receive too much light.

00:02:07.090 --> 00:02:12.287
Now, these two pieces of glass
here are the beam splitters.

00:02:12.287 --> 00:02:14.620
So we've seen that these beam
splitters-- basically what

00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:17.980
they do is that they will
split a section of the beam

00:02:17.980 --> 00:02:20.740
to one side and a section of
the beam to the other side.

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:24.370
In this case, it's
50/50 percent.

00:02:24.370 --> 00:02:26.170
Now, then, we have two mirrors.

00:02:26.170 --> 00:02:28.540
So as you can see,
there's one path here,

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:31.180
and the other path here.

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:34.240
The two paths that
now are going to be

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:36.490
combined by this second
beam splitter here.

00:02:36.490 --> 00:02:39.820
Sometimes, this is
called a beam combiner.

00:02:39.820 --> 00:02:44.470
And then they co-propagate here,
pass through this iris here,

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:46.720
and then in this case,
they're reflecting-- again,

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:50.620
these mirror are
going to the CCD.

00:02:50.620 --> 00:02:54.010
So essentially, what we have
here is these two plane waves

00:02:54.010 --> 00:02:57.430
that first are splitted and
then are combined back again

00:02:57.430 --> 00:02:58.640
together.

00:02:58.640 --> 00:03:01.660
And if the two plane waves
are exactly in line--

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:03.610
we see that we're not
supposed to see fringes

00:03:03.610 --> 00:03:05.650
because they are
exactly in line,

00:03:05.650 --> 00:03:09.530
but we learned also that if we
introduce a little angle here,

00:03:09.530 --> 00:03:13.810
now the planar wavefronts of
each plane wave will interfere,

00:03:13.810 --> 00:03:16.700
and then we're going to see
some sinusoidal pattern.

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:19.180
So this is exactly the same
as in the [? pieces. ?] One

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:21.670
of the problems that had what
would be the interference

00:03:21.670 --> 00:03:25.800
pattern in an xy
plane in this case.

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:28.440
In an xy plane,
[INAUDIBLE] two plane waves

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:31.420
propagating with a slightly
different k vectors.

00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:34.480
So now, let's look at
the interference pattern.

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:36.450
Now, this is here in
my computer screen.

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:43.930
So this is a video, real
time, of this interferometer.

00:03:43.930 --> 00:03:47.470
So as you can see, you
get very nice fringes

00:03:47.470 --> 00:03:49.840
of very bright and
very dark, so we

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:51.850
know that the
peaks are the proof

00:03:51.850 --> 00:03:55.150
of constructive interference,
the null destructive

00:03:55.150 --> 00:03:56.560
interference.

00:03:56.560 --> 00:03:59.170
And you also see
some vibration here,

00:03:59.170 --> 00:04:01.300
because we said that
these type of instruments

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:05.290
are very, very, very sensitive
to environmental conditions,

00:04:05.290 --> 00:04:08.872
and I'm actually going
to tap the table.

00:04:08.872 --> 00:04:10.330
Even if I just blow
some air, but I

00:04:10.330 --> 00:04:12.820
want to get some moisture
in there, in the optics,

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:15.700
but you can see
variations of the fringes.

00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:18.459
So then these type
of interferometers

00:04:18.459 --> 00:04:20.410
are used for
different measurements

00:04:20.410 --> 00:04:23.290
to calculate, for
instance, phases or measure

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:26.750
different profiles of
reflective optics, et cetera.

00:04:26.750 --> 00:04:28.450
So there are many
applications of

00:04:28.450 --> 00:04:30.310
these Mach-Zehnder
interferometers,

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:32.090
and the reason being
the sensitivity.

00:04:32.090 --> 00:04:34.420
Now, we also talked
about another thing--

00:04:34.420 --> 00:04:38.200
the period of this sinusoidal
pattern that we see

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:41.500
is proportional to the
angle of the plane waves.

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:44.080
So in this case, I'm going to
move one of the mirrors-- say,

00:04:44.080 --> 00:04:46.000
this mirror here--

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.010
to change one of the beam paths.

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:50.140
The other one is
going to remain fixed.

00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:53.300
So let me tilt it a little bit
and see what happens first.

00:04:57.120 --> 00:05:00.750
So we see that the period of
the plane wave is changing.

00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:05.020
In this case, I'm moving
it in in the y direction.

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:07.530
So now the period is larger.

00:05:07.530 --> 00:05:10.980
Does anyone want to tell me why
do you think it's happening?

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:12.870
Are the plane waves
more close to be

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:14.360
parallel, or further away?

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:31.548
Yep?

00:05:31.548 --> 00:05:33.590
STUDENT: Appears inversely
proportional to theta,

00:05:33.590 --> 00:05:36.440
so your period's smaller data.

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:38.710
JOSE DOMINGUEZ-CABALLERO:
Yes, exactly.

00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:41.080
So essentially,
here, by doing this,

00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:44.132
I'm making the plane waves
to be as in line as I can.

00:05:44.132 --> 00:05:46.090
And of course, since I'm
increasing the period,

00:05:46.090 --> 00:05:47.960
also the oscillations
will start increasing,

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:50.830
and now, we get these
artifacts due to the frame

00:05:50.830 --> 00:05:53.350
rate of the camera that are
going to be very noticeable,

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:56.080
I suppose, in Singapore.

00:05:56.080 --> 00:05:58.060
That's why I started
with a small fringe.

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:02.530
I can also change the
tilting of the fringe

00:06:02.530 --> 00:06:05.590
to do nice things like
this by basically changing

00:06:05.590 --> 00:06:09.280
the orientation of the mirrors.

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:11.320
All right, so now
what I'm going to do

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:13.780
is I'm going to block
one of these beam paths.

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:19.265
So we have a nice
plane wave here,

00:06:19.265 --> 00:06:23.030
and now, we are going
to repeat the aperture,

00:06:23.030 --> 00:06:26.240
this lead experiment
that I showed last time.

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:29.240
But today, we're going to
do it in different L regime.

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:31.970
So basically, we're going
to try to mimic physically

00:06:31.970 --> 00:06:35.090
the experiment that
Professor Barbastathis showed

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:38.270
in the video that he showed
in, I think, last lecture.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:48.070
All right, so we
have this slate here.

00:06:48.070 --> 00:06:49.600
Let me get it down a little bit.

00:06:54.620 --> 00:07:02.310
And I need to control
the intensity,

00:07:02.310 --> 00:07:05.230
so I'm going to move
this closer to the CCD.

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:07.420
This is as close as I can get.

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:11.550
So as you can see, there
is a plane wave hitting--

00:07:11.550 --> 00:07:13.050
let me just reduce the exposure.

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:21.670
There is a plane wave
hitting this slate,

00:07:21.670 --> 00:07:24.850
and you can see the
diffraction here happening

00:07:24.850 --> 00:07:27.250
in the discontinuity
when basically it

00:07:27.250 --> 00:07:28.620
hits the metal piece.

00:07:28.620 --> 00:07:30.890
And I can tune the size
here, and of course,

00:07:30.890 --> 00:07:33.880
if I make this larger,
the diffraction effects

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:35.980
appear less noticeable.

00:07:35.980 --> 00:07:37.900
But for a smaller slate--

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:42.920
let's do that-- it's
actually pretty nice.

00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:44.420
We see the nice
diffraction, but I'm

00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:46.600
going to increase
intensity, so you can see

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:50.750
the fringes that happen there.

00:07:50.750 --> 00:07:54.630
Now, let's see what
happens if I have it--

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:56.790
I fixed position, so
the size of this slate,

00:07:56.790 --> 00:08:02.090
and now I'm going to move it
along the optical axis back.

00:08:02.090 --> 00:08:06.410
So I'm propagating back.

00:08:06.410 --> 00:08:15.490
Let me just reduce the intensity
here, so we are somewhere here.

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:22.700
So now, I'm going
to go back, and you

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:25.310
can see how the diffraction
pattern changes.

00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:27.398
And this is
essentially the video.

00:08:27.398 --> 00:08:28.940
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Can you hear me?

00:08:28.940 --> 00:08:30.190
JOSE DOMINGUEZ-CABALLERO: Yes.

00:08:30.190 --> 00:08:31.690
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Can you go back

00:08:31.690 --> 00:08:34.010
where the fringe in
