00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:10.830
That's because the
scattering of the two edges

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:13.740
is actually out of phase,
so that the interference

00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:16.872
destructively at the center,
and you see an entire dark band.

00:09:16.872 --> 00:09:19.330
And then of course, in this
case, with a circular aperture,

00:09:19.330 --> 00:09:21.732
you see the Poisson
spot as a spot.

00:09:21.732 --> 00:09:23.190
In this case, it
is a vertical bar.

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:23.580
JOSE DOMINGUEZ-CABALLERO:
There you go.

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:24.612
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Yeah, that's perfect.

00:09:24.612 --> 00:09:25.710
Perfect, yeah.

00:09:25.710 --> 00:09:28.043
JOSE DOMINGUEZ-CABALLERO: So
here, you see the blinking.

00:09:28.043 --> 00:09:30.030
So this is dark, and
this would be bright.

00:09:33.988 --> 00:09:35.780
This would be the
blinking line, I suppose.

00:09:38.430 --> 00:09:44.670
Now, let me change it to
the other video that we saw,

00:09:44.670 --> 00:09:49.681
that was the circular aperture.

00:09:53.350 --> 00:09:56.260
So this is a circular
aperture of a fixed size.

00:09:56.260 --> 00:10:00.220
In this case, you can see,
when it's close to the camera,

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:03.340
again, as close as
I can get it to,

00:10:03.340 --> 00:10:05.975
you see refraction patterns.

00:10:05.975 --> 00:10:07.600
So now, this is very
nice, because what

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:09.017
we're supposed to
see here, again,

00:10:09.017 --> 00:10:13.382
is going to be that famous
Poisson spot or blinking spot.

00:10:13.382 --> 00:10:15.570
And before we see the
results that we, again,

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:20.340
saw in the movie, there's a nice
historical story about these.

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:27.270
In [INAUDIBLE],, Fresnel spent
a very nice paper to a contest

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:28.812
about the refraction of light.

00:10:28.812 --> 00:10:30.270
So at the time,
remember that there

00:10:30.270 --> 00:10:34.680
was all this controversy of
is light a wave or a particle.

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:38.610
So in the committee
judging these papers,

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:40.560
Poisson, a very
respected scientist,

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:42.360
was actually in the committee.

00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:44.310
And he saw Fresnel's
paper, and he was

00:10:44.310 --> 00:10:45.630
like, no, this has to be wrong.

00:10:45.630 --> 00:10:48.400
And he wanted to disprove it,
so he actually went and did

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:51.300
some calculations
and then proved

00:10:51.300 --> 00:10:56.370
that, if Fresnel was
right, what this means

00:10:56.370 --> 00:11:00.450
is that if you have, say, an
opening like this, somewhere

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:03.510
behind that opening, after
shining it with a plane wave,

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:06.080
you're supposed to
see a dark spot.

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:07.980
And that dark spot is
very counterintuitive

00:11:07.980 --> 00:11:09.775
because, basically,
you're supposed to see,

00:11:09.775 --> 00:11:12.150
from the geometrical optics,
all the light going straight

00:11:12.150 --> 00:11:12.650
through.

00:11:12.650 --> 00:11:17.850
So how could there be a very
dark spot in the center?

00:11:17.850 --> 00:11:20.220
So then basically, he
said, no, this is the proof

00:11:20.220 --> 00:11:23.670
that Fresnel's theory is wrong.

00:11:23.670 --> 00:11:27.540
But then another member in the
committee, Dominique Arago,

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:30.300
he actually went ahead
and did the experiment,

00:11:30.300 --> 00:11:33.450
and he saw this Poisson
spot experimentally.

00:11:33.450 --> 00:11:35.070
And then thanks to
that, of course,

00:11:35.070 --> 00:11:36.780
Fresnel won the contest.

00:11:36.780 --> 00:11:39.480
And now this, I guess, as
opposed to-- like as occurs

00:11:39.480 --> 00:11:40.380
to Poisson--

00:11:40.380 --> 00:11:43.100
it's called a Poisson spot.

00:11:43.100 --> 00:11:46.440
All right, let's see the
Poisson spot in action.

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:51.400
So I'm going to go-- here,
you see it in bright, dark.

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:53.790
I'm going to go
even further away.

00:11:56.430 --> 00:11:59.950
So I'm moving it back, and
you see the blinking spot.

00:11:59.950 --> 00:12:00.925
Trying to do it slowly.

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:04.970
Going to go back.

00:12:04.970 --> 00:12:06.304
Can you see it in Singapore?

00:12:11.512 --> 00:12:12.470
I guess that was a yes.

00:12:17.160 --> 00:12:18.742
Cool.

00:12:18.742 --> 00:12:20.950
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: They're
very beautiful actually.

00:12:20.950 --> 00:12:22.992
JOSE DOMINGUEZ-CABALLERO:
Yes, they're very nice.

