00:27:57.630 --> 00:28:03.120
and then you get a plus 1 above
and a minus 1 diffraction order

00:28:03.120 --> 00:28:04.140
below.

00:28:04.140 --> 00:28:09.000
So this is the typical behavior
of a sinusoidal amplitude

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:10.350
grating.

00:28:10.350 --> 00:28:12.720
Now, if I play the same
thing for the first grating,

00:28:12.720 --> 00:28:14.170
there's two things to notice.

00:28:14.170 --> 00:28:16.480
First of all, there's
no moire at all here.

00:28:16.480 --> 00:28:18.330
That's because the
phase grating does not

00:28:18.330 --> 00:28:22.060
modulate the magnitude of
the electric field at all.

00:28:22.060 --> 00:28:24.600
So in other words,
at the entrance

00:28:24.600 --> 00:28:27.210
toward the grating
itself, the grating

00:28:27.210 --> 00:28:29.700
looks just like an
empty transparency.

00:28:29.700 --> 00:28:32.490
It has not changed the
magnitude of the field.

00:28:32.490 --> 00:28:34.890
What it has done, it
has changed the phase,

00:28:34.890 --> 00:28:36.930
and because the
phase of the field

00:28:36.930 --> 00:28:40.380
got modulated inside
this slit over here,

00:28:40.380 --> 00:28:42.780
what you will see when I
play the grating is, again,

00:28:42.780 --> 00:28:44.280
that it splits.

00:28:44.280 --> 00:28:45.940
But now, it splits
into more than one.

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:49.620
It splits into, in this case,
you can see very clearly

00:28:49.620 --> 00:28:52.400
five diffraction orders.

00:28:52.400 --> 00:28:54.420
You can see very
clearly, there is

00:28:54.420 --> 00:28:59.850
one in the center, then
another one and another one.

00:28:59.850 --> 00:29:03.330
So these are the plus 1, plus
2, and then at the bottom,

00:29:03.330 --> 00:29:08.740
you have minus 1, minus
2 diffraction orders.

00:29:08.740 --> 00:29:13.810
So it is, in some ways,
similar to the amplitude case,

00:29:13.810 --> 00:29:18.090
but in this case, we'll get
more diffraction orders.

00:29:18.090 --> 00:29:21.240
And so I guess what I
would like to do now

00:29:21.240 --> 00:29:24.720
is I will try to explain
what is the difference,

00:29:24.720 --> 00:29:28.740
and why the phase grating gives
us more diffraction order.

00:29:28.740 --> 00:29:32.010
I should say, by the way,
that the sinusoidal--

00:29:32.010 --> 00:29:34.900
I want to emphasize the
sinusoidal amplitude

00:29:34.900 --> 00:29:37.610
grating gives us only three--

00:29:37.610 --> 00:29:40.005
the 0 order, the plus
1, and the minus 1.

00:29:40.005 --> 00:29:42.870
In general, other
types of gratings,

00:29:42.870 --> 00:29:46.290
for example binary or
phase gratings and so on,

00:29:46.290 --> 00:29:48.560
they give us more than
three diffraction orders.

00:29:52.980 --> 00:29:56.588
So first of all, let's look
at the physical picture.

00:29:56.588 --> 00:29:58.380
So I'll start with the
sinusoidal amplitude

00:29:58.380 --> 00:30:01.287
because this is the
simplest possible grating,

00:30:01.287 --> 00:30:03.870
and let's look at the physical
picture of what's going on here

00:30:03.870 --> 00:30:06.810
and why we get this
diffraction order.

00:30:06.810 --> 00:30:09.200
So if I have a plane
wave impinging-- oh,

00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:14.020
so again, this symbol, being
Greek, I have an advantage,

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:14.520
I guess.

00:30:14.520 --> 00:30:16.020
I can recognize it.

00:30:16.020 --> 00:30:18.060
It is the uppercase
lambda, so we'll

00:30:18.060 --> 00:30:20.320
use the symbol lowercase--

00:30:20.320 --> 00:30:23.410
control, may I have the paper?

00:30:23.410 --> 00:30:25.180
Actually, I already
have the paper, do I?

00:30:25.180 --> 00:30:26.310
Yeah.

00:30:26.310 --> 00:30:31.040
So this symbol that we
use for the wavelength

00:30:31.040 --> 00:30:35.325
is the lowercase lambda.

00:30:38.520 --> 00:30:42.030
This symbol that we use
generally for a special period

00:30:42.030 --> 00:30:42.870
is the uppercase.

00:30:47.850 --> 00:30:49.350
It may sound a
little bit ridiculous

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:53.870
that I emphasize it so much, but
believe me, in previous years,

00:30:53.870 --> 00:30:57.960
all the generations of students
have been endlessly confused

00:30:57.960 --> 00:30:59.185
by the lambda and the lambda.

00:30:59.185 --> 00:31:00.560
So I would like
to emphasize it--

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:02.190
these are two different symbols.

00:31:02.190 --> 00:31:04.500
We use the lower case
for the wavelength

00:31:04.500 --> 00:31:08.370
and the upper case for
the spatial period.

00:31:08.370 --> 00:31:09.150
So that's it then.

00:31:09.150 --> 00:31:11.790
That's the period, and
the inverse of that--

00:31:11.790 --> 00:31:14.700
the inverse of a period
generally is a frequency.

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:18.140
So since now we have a spatial
period, the inverse [? u0, ?]

00:31:18.140 --> 00:31:21.450
we'll call this
special frequency.

00:31:21.450 --> 00:31:23.700
And let's illuminate
this grating now

00:31:23.700 --> 00:31:26.040
with an incident plane wave.

00:31:26.040 --> 00:31:29.190
So throughout this lecture, I
will be illuminating gratings

00:31:29.190 --> 00:31:31.950
with plane waves on axis.

00:31:31.950 --> 00:31:34.740
In the homework that
I've posted today,

00:31:34.740 --> 00:31:37.290
and actually just became
visible a few minutes ago,

00:31:37.290 --> 00:31:39.120
in the homework,
you will see what

00:31:39.120 --> 00:31:42.510
happens if you illuminate the
grating with a tilted plane

00:31:42.510 --> 00:31:45.010
wave or with a spherical wave.

00:31:45.010 --> 00:31:46.170
This is also possible.

00:31:46.170 --> 00:31:49.380
You can illuminate a
grate in any way you like.

00:31:49.380 --> 00:31:51.520
Now, we'll start with
the simplest case,

00:31:51.520 --> 00:31:54.540
which is on axis plane wave.

00:31:54.540 --> 00:31:56.610
So we don't know yet
what's going to happen,

00:31:56.610 --> 00:31:57.650
but we know one thing.

00:31:57.650 --> 00:32:00.240
We know Huygen's principal,
and Huygen's says

00:32:00.240 --> 00:32:04.380
that, at each point where
the grating is transmissive,

00:32:04.380 --> 00:32:06.350
we'll get point sources.

00:32:06.350 --> 00:32:09.000
So of course, I do not
only get only these two,

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:12.610
I get the point
source here, which

00:32:12.610 --> 00:32:15.820
is very strong because this is
the location where the grating

00:32:15.820 --> 00:32:17.560
has maximum transmission.

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:20.930
Next to it, I will
get another point--

00:32:20.930 --> 00:32:24.820
another Huygen's point source
that is slightly attenuated.

00:32:24.820 --> 00:32:27.190
Then next to it, another
one that is slightly more

00:32:27.190 --> 00:32:29.620
attenuated, another
one, another one.

00:32:29.620 --> 00:32:32.170
There comes a point here where
the grating is totally black,

00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:36.070
that it is totally absorbing.

00:32:36.070 --> 00:32:39.730
Therefore, there's is a missing
Huygen's source over here,

00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:41.920
and then as I move on
along the optical axis,

00:32:41.920 --> 00:32:45.250
I will get more Huygen's point
sources that are progressively

00:32:45.250 --> 00:32:46.540
less attenuated.

00:32:46.540 --> 00:32:48.600
And then finally, I
get over here where

00:32:48.600 --> 00:32:51.550
I have another strong,
as strong as possible,

00:32:51.550 --> 00:32:53.590
Huygen's point source.

00:32:53.590 --> 00:32:55.800
So we derived an integral.

00:32:55.800 --> 00:33:01.300
Professor Sheppard last week
[INAUDIBLE] of an integral that

00:33:01.300 --> 00:33:05.350
allows us to basically
sum the contributions

00:33:05.350 --> 00:33:08.470
from all these
Huygen's point sources

00:33:08.470 --> 00:33:11.530
and derive different
L diffracted field

00:33:11.530 --> 00:33:13.910
after the grating.

00:33:13.910 --> 00:33:17.660
So of course, this integral,
we call the Fresnel integral,

00:33:17.660 --> 00:33:20.540
and here is another linguistic
lesson-- this time in French,

00:33:20.540 --> 00:33:22.230
not in Greek.

00:33:22.230 --> 00:33:27.310
This is pronounced "Freh-nell."

00:33:27.310 --> 00:33:29.080
The S is silent.

00:33:29.080 --> 00:33:32.350
So if you go to a conference,
and you say "Fres-nell,"

00:33:32.350 --> 00:33:35.560
people will conclude that
you don't know optics.

00:33:35.560 --> 00:33:37.030
So part of knowing
optics is part

00:33:37.030 --> 00:33:41.670
of knowing the French and the
Greek language, I suppose.

00:33:41.670 --> 00:33:44.080
I'm joking, of course,
but it's still actually,

00:33:44.080 --> 00:33:47.940
professionals are like
children, who are vicious.

00:33:47.940 --> 00:33:50.230
If we see someone make a
silly mistake like this,

00:33:50.230 --> 00:33:52.117
say "Fres-nell"
instead of "Freh-nell,"

00:33:52.117 --> 00:33:52.950
we make fun of them.

00:33:52.950 --> 00:33:55.590
And you don't want
to be made fun

00:33:55.590 --> 00:33:57.820
of in a professional setting.

00:33:57.820 --> 00:34:00.420
So always remember, this
is pronounced "Freh-nell,"

00:34:00.420 --> 00:34:02.400
not "Fres-nell."

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:04.590
So the Fresnel
integral, therefore,

00:34:04.590 --> 00:34:07.830
allows us to compute the
field, the diffracted field,

00:34:07.830 --> 00:34:09.300
after the grating.

00:34:09.300 --> 00:34:12.989
But we will not do it here
because the Fresnel integral,

00:34:12.989 --> 00:34:14.670
in this case, is awful.

00:34:14.670 --> 00:34:16.920
It is very difficult to compute.

00:34:16.920 --> 00:34:18.870
However, I will show
you that, by using

00:34:18.870 --> 00:34:22.290
very simple physical
arguments, we can nevertheless

00:34:22.290 --> 00:34:25.020
derive the Fresnel
diffracted field anyway

00:34:25.020 --> 00:34:31.214
without making use of this
nasty Fresnel integral.

00:34:33.790 --> 00:34:37.860
So let's go back to our
Huygen's picture here.

00:34:37.860 --> 00:34:41.830
I would just consider this two
point sources of Huygen's which

00:34:41.830 --> 00:34:43.112
are the strongest.

00:34:43.112 --> 00:34:44.820
And this is, of course,
an approximation,

00:34:44.820 --> 00:34:46.780
a simplification, but
it will still give us

00:34:46.780 --> 00:34:48.489
the correct physical picture.

00:34:48.489 --> 00:34:50.230
That's why I'm doing it.

00:34:50.230 --> 00:34:52.630
So basically, over
here, you can see

00:34:52.630 --> 00:34:55.570
that these are point sources,
so they basically emit light

00:34:55.570 --> 00:34:57.970
in all possible directions.

00:34:57.970 --> 00:35:02.650
So I will pick one
arbitrary direction,

00:35:02.650 --> 00:35:05.320
and I will call it theta.

00:35:05.320 --> 00:35:08.560
So here is a ray, if you
wish, a ray emanating

00:35:08.560 --> 00:35:12.760
from this Huygen's point
source at angle theta,

00:35:12.760 --> 00:35:16.210
and here's another ray emanating
from the next Huygen's point

00:35:16.210 --> 00:35:18.970
source at the same angle theta.

00:35:18.970 --> 00:35:22.980
Now, these rays-- are they
the same or different?

00:35:22.980 --> 00:35:25.950
Geometrical optics
says they're the same,

00:35:25.950 --> 00:35:27.160
but now, we know better.

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:30.900
We know that these
are not really bullets

00:35:30.900 --> 00:35:32.650
that propagate like particles.

00:35:32.650 --> 00:35:34.490
These are actually waves.

00:35:34.490 --> 00:35:37.410
And if you compare
the wave emitted here

00:35:37.410 --> 00:35:40.860
and the wave emitted
there, if you draw a line

00:35:40.860 --> 00:35:46.420
perpendicular to these waves,
this would be the wavefront.

00:35:46.420 --> 00:35:49.950
So you can see, easily now,
that if you compare the wave

00:35:49.950 --> 00:35:54.210
on the lower ray with a
wave with the upper ray,

00:35:54.210 --> 00:35:58.950
you can see that the wave in the
lower ray is actually delayed.

00:35:58.950 --> 00:36:00.900
It has traveled the
longer distance.

00:36:00.900 --> 00:36:04.920
Therefore, it is delayed by
a certain amount with respect

00:36:04.920 --> 00:36:06.950
to the ray that is below.

00:36:06.950 --> 00:36:09.300
And the way, of course,
to compute this delay

00:36:09.300 --> 00:36:14.070
is to draw an orthogonal
triangle here.

00:36:14.070 --> 00:36:20.400
This side of the triangle
is actually the wavefront.

00:36:20.400 --> 00:36:24.900
This side of the triangle
is the phase delay,

00:36:24.900 --> 00:36:28.420
and the hypotenuse of the
triangle is the period--

00:36:28.420 --> 00:36:30.270
is the special
period of the grating

00:36:30.270 --> 00:36:32.550
that we denoted as lambda.

00:36:32.550 --> 00:36:34.500
So by using the
Pythagoras theorem,

00:36:34.500 --> 00:36:39.100
then, we can actually
compute the phase delay,

00:36:39.100 --> 00:36:42.220
and we can compute--

00:36:42.220 --> 00:36:44.210
there's, of course, a typo here.

00:36:44.210 --> 00:36:47.000
Let me fix it right away, and
I will post a fix in the notes.

00:36:54.970 --> 00:37:00.080
Anyway, I think it's better
if I don't fix it now,

00:37:00.080 --> 00:37:04.980
but the correct equation over
there should say the optical

00:37:04.980 --> 00:37:09.150
path length difference--
that's what OPLD means--

00:37:09.150 --> 00:37:14.930
equals lambda, the grating
period, times sine theta.

00:37:14.930 --> 00:37:15.680
Sorry about that.

00:37:15.680 --> 00:37:17.810
These notes came from
another old [? convention ?]

00:37:17.810 --> 00:37:19.630
where the period
was denoted as d.

00:37:26.350 --> 00:37:28.180
So with this little
fix, that OPLD

00:37:28.180 --> 00:37:32.230
equals the period of the
grating times sine theta,

00:37:32.230 --> 00:37:36.640
we can see now that, if
this quantity of OPLD

00:37:36.640 --> 00:37:44.130
equals a wavelength, then the
two rays are actually in phase.

00:37:44.130 --> 00:37:46.060
And not only one
wavelength-- it might

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:48.720
equal two wavelengths,
three wavelengths,

00:37:48.720 --> 00:37:51.070
any integral number
of wavelengths.

00:37:51.070 --> 00:37:52.770
Then these two
waves are in phase.

00:37:52.770 --> 00:37:56.130
Therefore, they
interfere constructively.

00:37:56.130 --> 00:37:57.520
And this is the key, now--

00:37:57.520 --> 00:38:02.260
the constructive interference
of waves in these specific,

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:06.940
now, directions is what we
call diffraction orders,

00:38:06.940 --> 00:38:10.250
that Pepe very beautifully
showed you earlier.

00:38:10.250 --> 00:38:15.880
And you also saw them in
my simulation in Matlab.

00:38:15.880 --> 00:38:20.500
And so q here, the
quantity q, is an integer.

00:38:20.500 --> 00:38:22.620
It is meant to
denote an integer,

00:38:22.620 --> 00:38:26.660
and we can derive this now.

00:38:26.660 --> 00:38:33.200
So we can derive the sine
of the angle of the q,

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:37.010
over the qth, I guess,
diffraction order where

00:38:37.010 --> 00:38:40.800
qth might be first,
second, third, and so on.

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:43.040
So q runs 1, 2, 3, and so on.

00:38:43.040 --> 00:38:45.410
And of course,
because typically, we

00:38:45.410 --> 00:38:47.630
operate in the
paraxial approximation,

00:38:47.630 --> 00:38:50.600
we can also drop the
sign here and say simply

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:53.530
that the plus/minus
1 diffraction

00:38:53.530 --> 00:38:55.760
order is propagating
at an angle that

00:38:55.760 --> 00:38:57.890
is given by this
ratio over there,

00:38:57.890 --> 00:39:02.420
the ratio of the
small Greek lambda

00:39:02.420 --> 00:39:06.560
to the big Greek lambda, that
is the ratio of the wavelength

00:39:06.560 --> 00:39:08.292
over the period.

00:39:08.292 --> 00:39:10.000
And you can see
immediately, for example,

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:15.250
that if I make the
grating period smaller

00:39:15.250 --> 00:39:17.530
than the wavelength,
I will get in trouble

00:39:17.530 --> 00:39:20.770
because this sine over there
will attempt to become bigger

00:39:20.770 --> 00:39:21.940
than 1.

00:39:21.940 --> 00:39:23.810
Anybody knows what
happens in this case

00:39:23.810 --> 00:39:26.560
if I make the grating
period smaller than lambda,

00:39:26.560 --> 00:39:28.127
than the wavelength?

00:39:31.110 --> 00:39:34.450
Mr. [INAUDIBLE]?

00:39:34.450 --> 00:39:36.970
Yeah, actually, I can do--

00:39:36.970 --> 00:39:39.520
I can make a period
smaller than a wavelength.

00:39:39.520 --> 00:39:41.160
What will happen
then is I will get

00:39:41.160 --> 00:39:43.330
what is called an
evanescent wave,

00:39:43.330 --> 00:39:45.530
so I will not get a
diffraction order anymore.

00:39:45.530 --> 00:39:47.860
I'll get an evanescent
wave from the grating,

00:39:47.860 --> 00:39:50.540
and this is a term
that we've seen before.

00:39:50.540 --> 00:39:52.580
We haven't defined
yet, mathematically,

00:39:52.580 --> 00:39:56.350
but I want to alert you that,
basically, an evanescent

00:39:56.350 --> 00:39:59.500
wave is an exponential
decay of a diffracted field.

00:39:59.500 --> 00:40:04.120
So you do not quite get a
diffracted order anymore.

00:40:04.120 --> 00:40:08.350
For the purposes of the class,
in the next few lectures

00:40:08.350 --> 00:40:12.400
at least, definitely for the
next three or four weeks,

00:40:12.400 --> 00:40:17.260
we will assume that the
grating period is much larger

00:40:17.260 --> 00:40:18.370
than the wavelength.

00:40:18.370 --> 00:40:21.130
So therefore, this quantity
is always less than 1,

00:40:21.130 --> 00:40:24.490
and the sine is always
properly less than 1.

00:40:24.490 --> 00:40:28.900
And we can solve it, so we can
get the real and not evanescent

00:40:28.900 --> 00:40:29.780
diffraction order.

00:40:33.270 --> 00:40:34.543
I think my computer--

00:40:39.750 --> 00:40:41.705
so as I said
before, the plus 1--

00:40:41.705 --> 00:40:42.830
this is actually arbitrary.

00:40:42.830 --> 00:40:46.240
I can call plus 1--

00:40:46.240 --> 00:40:49.630
by convention, the plus
1 is the one that goes--

00:40:49.630 --> 00:40:54.995
if we denote the light--

00:40:54.995 --> 00:40:56.860
as in geometrical
optics, the light

00:40:56.860 --> 00:40:59.860
always goes from left to right.

00:40:59.860 --> 00:41:05.240
And the angle is
positive if it is acute

00:41:05.240 --> 00:41:08.280
measured counterclockwise
from the optical axis.

00:41:08.280 --> 00:41:11.420
So that is why this is the
plus first diffraction order.

00:41:11.420 --> 00:41:14.240
It has a positive propagation
angle, and then the one

00:41:14.240 --> 00:41:15.870
that has negative
propagation angle,

00:41:15.870 --> 00:41:20.910
we'll call it minus
first diffraction order.

00:41:20.910 --> 00:41:23.920
The 0th diffraction
order is the one

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:29.710
that has theta equals 0
that is propagating on axis.

00:41:29.710 --> 00:41:32.470
That is also known as a DC term.

00:41:32.470 --> 00:41:35.120
Now, for those of you who
are electrical engineers,

00:41:35.120 --> 00:41:38.660
the term DC already alerts
you to some kind of a Fourier

00:41:38.660 --> 00:41:42.650
transform or some kind of
a frequency representation.

00:41:42.650 --> 00:41:45.940
We will see later that, indeed,
light propagating on axes

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:50.440
can be thought of as the
equivalent of a DC component

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:55.020
in Fourier series decomposition.

00:41:55.020 --> 00:42:00.930
For now, let's take it
as a term, as a sort of--

00:42:00.930 --> 00:42:04.270
what do you call
this-- as a jargon,

00:42:04.270 --> 00:42:06.830
and we'll see later why
we call this the DC term.

00:42:11.350 --> 00:42:13.750
This is a mathematical
derivation

00:42:13.750 --> 00:42:16.420
that we can do in order
to actually become

00:42:16.420 --> 00:42:20.020
a little bit more quantitative
and a little bit more correct.

00:42:20.020 --> 00:42:22.310
So the mathematical
definition is very simple.

00:42:22.310 --> 00:42:24.850
We start with the
expression for the grating.

00:42:28.020 --> 00:42:30.630
Then we decompose the
cosine into the two

00:42:30.630 --> 00:42:34.690
complex exponentials that
we can [? write ?] it.

00:42:34.690 --> 00:42:41.410
And then what we do is we
simply make a substitution

00:42:41.410 --> 00:42:44.380
according to the equation
that I saw before already.

00:42:44.380 --> 00:42:52.410
We say that 1 over lambda
equals sine theta upon lambda.

00:42:52.410 --> 00:42:54.550
This may seem arbitrary,
but I can always

00:42:54.550 --> 00:42:57.940
do it because lambda--

00:42:57.940 --> 00:43:01.010
I'm sorry [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:01.010 --> 00:43:02.180
Uh-oh, we're out of focus.

00:43:05.910 --> 00:43:07.470
Anyway, you cannot
see the question,

00:43:07.470 --> 00:43:10.290
but you can certainly see
this substitution here.

00:43:10.290 --> 00:43:12.310
And I cannot-- thank you.

00:43:12.310 --> 00:43:16.110
So we can always
do the substitution

00:43:16.110 --> 00:43:20.440
by defining sine theta to be
the ratio of the wavelength

00:43:20.440 --> 00:43:24.240
over the period,
and we can also make

00:43:24.240 --> 00:43:27.150
a substitution of [? u0, ?]
the special frequency as I

00:43:27.150 --> 00:43:28.740
defined it before.

00:43:28.740 --> 00:43:29.790
The point is not that.

00:43:29.790 --> 00:43:32.730
The point is that each
one of these terms

00:43:32.730 --> 00:43:35.910
actually is recognizable
as a plane wave.

00:43:35.910 --> 00:43:40.735
And now, we'll really
need my transparency here.

00:43:40.735 --> 00:43:45.810
So if you recall, when
we derived plane waves--

00:43:45.810 --> 00:43:47.330
we did this some time ago.

00:43:47.330 --> 00:43:49.500
Actually, I think
Professor Sheppard did it

00:43:49.500 --> 00:43:51.450
in the context of
electromagnetics.

00:43:51.450 --> 00:43:54.570
The way we write a
plane wave is like this.

00:44:31.163 --> 00:44:33.580
These are what you will see
if you go back into your notes

00:44:33.580 --> 00:44:36.620
by about two or three lectures.

00:44:36.620 --> 00:44:38.380
If you have a plane
wave propagating

00:44:38.380 --> 00:44:41.080
in the direction
of this arrow here,

00:44:41.080 --> 00:44:43.790
then the expression
that I put above

00:44:43.790 --> 00:44:48.460
is actually the phasor for
the electromagnetic field

00:44:48.460 --> 00:44:50.470
describing that plane wave.

00:44:50.470 --> 00:44:56.750
And if, in addition, we say that
the grating is at z equals 0--

00:44:56.750 --> 00:44:58.790
which I can always do.

00:44:58.790 --> 00:45:02.140
I can define my axis so that
the grating is located at

00:45:02.140 --> 00:45:03.230
z equals 0--

00:45:03.230 --> 00:45:05.540
then this term will
actually disappear.

00:45:05.540 --> 00:45:08.300
And you can recognize
now this expression

00:45:08.300 --> 00:45:12.890
that is left for the plane
wave is the same that you have

00:45:12.890 --> 00:45:17.120
already here with
the complex exponent,

00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:20.030
provided you make the
substitution that we

00:45:20.030 --> 00:45:23.400
had before, provided you
make the substitution--

00:45:23.400 --> 00:45:23.900
this one.

00:45:26.960 --> 00:45:29.360
With a substitution,
the grating itself

00:45:29.360 --> 00:45:32.370
becomes like the expression
for not just one, but actually

00:45:32.370 --> 00:45:33.800
three plane waves.

00:45:33.800 --> 00:45:36.020
And what are the
three plane waves?

00:45:36.020 --> 00:45:43.470
Well, here is one, which is the
plus first diffraction order.

00:45:43.470 --> 00:45:47.610
There's a plane wave
propagating at angle theta.

00:45:47.610 --> 00:45:50.850
Then the next one, the
constant is actually

00:45:50.850 --> 00:45:52.950
the DC term that
propagates on axis,

00:45:52.950 --> 00:45:58.500
because if you substitute
theta equals 0 here,

00:45:58.500 --> 00:46:01.560
then this entire thing
disappears, so you just

00:46:01.560 --> 00:46:02.610
have the constant.

00:46:02.610 --> 00:46:06.070
That is a plane wave
propagating on axis.

00:46:06.070 --> 00:46:09.143
And finally, this
term is propagating

00:46:09.143 --> 00:46:10.560
at the negative
angle, and this is

00:46:10.560 --> 00:46:14.970
what you call the minus
1 diffraction order.

00:46:14.970 --> 00:46:17.760
So this may seem a little bit
like mathematical trickery,

00:46:17.760 --> 00:46:20.400
but has a very nice
physical interpretation,

00:46:20.400 --> 00:46:24.600
if only you recall our
convention for the phasor

00:46:24.600 --> 00:46:28.820
expression of plane waves.

00:46:28.820 --> 00:46:32.980
The rest is relatively
straightforward.

00:46:32.980 --> 00:46:36.810
A sinusoidal phase
grating, as Pepe mentioned,

00:46:36.810 --> 00:46:39.270
is basically a
grating which does not

00:46:39.270 --> 00:46:42.250
modulate the amplitude, but
the phase of the optical field.

00:46:42.250 --> 00:46:43.930
And you can do it in two ways.

00:46:43.930 --> 00:46:45.420
One is what I saw here.

00:46:45.420 --> 00:46:48.520
That is known as a
surface relief grating,

00:46:48.520 --> 00:46:49.740
which has been processed.

00:46:49.740 --> 00:46:51.510
Typically, this is
done by chemical--

00:46:51.510 --> 00:46:55.530
by optical exposure and then
chemical development, that

00:46:55.530 --> 00:46:57.860
causes the surface
of, typically,

00:46:57.860 --> 00:47:04.200
a polymer or a properly prepared
colloidal, colloidal glass.

00:47:04.200 --> 00:47:08.700
It causes the surface to pick
up a sinusoidal modulation

00:47:08.700 --> 00:47:09.610
like this.

00:47:09.610 --> 00:47:14.160
So because the material
has a refractive index n,

00:47:14.160 --> 00:47:16.200
you can see that
light, depending

00:47:16.200 --> 00:47:19.860
if you take a ray, depending
on where it hits this material,

00:47:19.860 --> 00:47:23.920
it might suffer a
different phase delay.

00:47:23.920 --> 00:47:26.010
Another way that
Pepe mentioned is you

00:47:26.010 --> 00:47:28.650
might actually have a
flat piece of material

00:47:28.650 --> 00:47:31.230
and modulate the index
of refraction inside.

00:47:31.230 --> 00:47:33.390
Again, that would
have a similar effect.

00:47:33.390 --> 00:47:36.510
The complex transmission
function would be of this form.

00:47:36.510 --> 00:47:40.500
It would be an
exponential whose value

00:47:40.500 --> 00:47:45.240
depends upon the optical
thickness of the material

00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:46.680
that the light went through.

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:52.150
You can see the period here,
and you can see the phase delay.

00:47:52.150 --> 00:47:54.750
So the phase delay,
of course, depends

00:47:54.750 --> 00:47:56.880
on the difference between
the index of refraction

00:47:56.880 --> 00:47:59.115
inside the material and
the index of refraction

00:47:59.115 --> 00:48:02.350
in the surrounding
middle that is air.

00:48:02.350 --> 00:48:05.270
So that's the
expression over there,

00:48:05.270 --> 00:48:07.360
and this is, of course,
the phase contrast

00:48:07.360 --> 00:48:10.410
that we mentioned before,
when we defined the grating.

00:48:10.410 --> 00:48:13.060
And in order, now,
to figure out what

00:48:13.060 --> 00:48:15.310
happens after this
grating, I will

00:48:15.310 --> 00:48:22.540
have to resort to mathematical,
again, trickery, I guess.

00:48:22.540 --> 00:48:24.880
If you go to books
of optical tables,

00:48:24.880 --> 00:48:28.840
you can find very easily
that this expression can also

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:32.830
be written as a
sum, as a sum that

00:48:32.830 --> 00:48:37.300
involves some kind of
nasty Bessel functions.

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:38.930
We don't even have
to worry about this,

00:48:38.930 --> 00:48:41.470
but what we will go
ahead and add in a second

00:48:41.470 --> 00:48:43.870
is that each one of
these Bessel functions

00:48:43.870 --> 00:48:49.000
corresponds to diffraction
order for this grating.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:52.600
And the way you can see this
is if you rewrite the grating

00:48:52.600 --> 00:48:54.200
like this.

00:48:54.200 --> 00:48:57.670
So this is now simply using
a mathematical formula,

00:48:57.670 --> 00:49:02.260
but now, if you actually do
the same trick I did here,

00:49:02.260 --> 00:49:06.550
if you recognize that each one
of these complex exponentials

00:49:06.550 --> 00:49:09.730
basically corresponds
to the plane wave,

00:49:09.730 --> 00:49:13.570
then you can see that
what I've written there,

00:49:13.570 --> 00:49:16.030
it came out of a book of
mathematical formulas,

00:49:16.030 --> 00:49:18.450
but physically, it
contains an amplitude

00:49:18.450 --> 00:49:21.760
that is given by the value
of a Bessel function.

00:49:21.760 --> 00:49:24.910
But then more importantly,
it contains a sequence

00:49:24.910 --> 00:49:27.900
of plane waves that are
known as diffraction orders,

00:49:27.900 --> 00:49:32.730
and the propagation angle of
the plane wave indexed by q

00:49:32.730 --> 00:49:35.470
is given by this explanation
here, the same expression

00:49:35.470 --> 00:49:36.740
that they had before.

00:49:36.740 --> 00:49:39.700
So these are then the
diffraction orders

00:49:39.700 --> 00:49:42.060
for the sinusoidal
phase grating.

00:49:45.270 --> 00:49:48.180
Even more generally,
if you don't

00:49:48.180 --> 00:49:50.670
have a sinusoidal
grating, but still

00:49:50.670 --> 00:49:57.800
some kind of a periodic
grating with arbitrary shape,

00:49:57.800 --> 00:50:00.800
and also possibly you
might even have absorption,

00:50:00.800 --> 00:50:06.410
so this grating truly
implements a complex amplitude

00:50:06.410 --> 00:50:09.230
transmission, which is
nevertheless periodic.

00:50:09.230 --> 00:50:12.350
You may recall from
your basic math

00:50:12.350 --> 00:50:15.050
that you have an arbitrary
complex periodic function,

00:50:15.050 --> 00:50:17.720
you can write it as
a Fourier series.

00:50:17.720 --> 00:50:19.460
And in this case,
the Fourier series

00:50:19.460 --> 00:50:21.440
also has the same
physical meaning

00:50:21.440 --> 00:50:25.220
as the one I did before,
the Fourier series

00:50:25.220 --> 00:50:28.450
expansion coefficients.

00:50:28.450 --> 00:50:31.900
And actually, the amplitudes
and the harmonics-- these

00:50:31.900 --> 00:50:33.760
are called harmonics,
if you recall.

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:36.430
The harmonics of the
Fourier series themselves

00:50:36.430 --> 00:50:39.610
now correspond to plane
waves that were previously

00:50:39.610 --> 00:50:41.230
called diffraction orders.

00:50:41.230 --> 00:50:43.300
So then you can see
that each Fourier series

00:50:43.300 --> 00:50:47.140
coefficient actually corresponds
to a separate diffraction

00:50:47.140 --> 00:50:47.640
order.

00:50:50.890 --> 00:50:55.640
And in addition, recall, again,
Professor Sheppard last week.

00:50:55.640 --> 00:50:58.870
He mentioned that if you
have an optical field,

00:50:58.870 --> 00:51:02.770
and you take the magnitude
squared of its phasor,

00:51:02.770 --> 00:51:06.400
then what you get is actually
the amount of energy that

00:51:06.400 --> 00:51:10.970
propagates that is
carried by this field.

00:51:10.970 --> 00:51:14.290
So therefore, the magnitude
squared of the Fourier series

00:51:14.290 --> 00:51:17.530
coefficient actually
corresponds to the energy

00:51:17.530 --> 00:51:20.920
that goes into each
separate diffraction order.

00:51:20.920 --> 00:51:22.960
So in this case,
so they're called

00:51:22.960 --> 00:51:24.002
diffraction efficiencies.

00:51:24.002 --> 00:51:25.918
And I should have mentioned
earlier, actually,

00:51:25.918 --> 00:51:26.665
but I forgot--

00:51:42.590 --> 00:51:47.770
so in the case of the
sinusoidal amplitude grating,

00:51:47.770 --> 00:51:49.490
the diffraction
efficiencies are given

00:51:49.490 --> 00:51:51.980
by the squares of
the coefficients that

00:51:51.980 --> 00:51:54.410
go in front of each plane wave.

00:51:54.410 --> 00:51:59.050
So you can see that
approximately-- how much--

00:51:59.050 --> 00:52:04.390
25% of the energy is
going into the 0 order.

00:52:04.390 --> 00:52:06.650
It is propagating on axis.

00:52:06.650 --> 00:52:09.170
And let's assume that
the contrast is 1.

00:52:09.170 --> 00:52:13.420
In that case, approximately
12.5% of the energy

00:52:13.420 --> 00:52:16.750
is going into each
diffraction order.

00:52:16.750 --> 00:52:19.180
That is 1/8.

00:52:19.180 --> 00:52:21.690
If I sum them up, how
much do they transmit?

00:52:28.110 --> 00:52:33.120
25% plus 12.5% plus
[INAUDIBLE] 12.5%--

00:52:33.120 --> 00:52:34.480
50%, right?

00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:35.730
What happens to the other 50%?

00:52:43.856 --> 00:52:45.442
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:52:45.442 --> 00:52:47.150
STUDENT: I think there
possibly maybe had

00:52:47.150 --> 00:52:49.850
a plus/minus 3 order
or something, I mean,

00:52:49.850 --> 00:52:50.845
other orders?

00:52:50.845 --> 00:52:53.220
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: That is
plausible, but in this case,

00:52:53.220 --> 00:52:55.800
we derived only
three orders-- the 0,

00:52:55.800 --> 00:52:58.833
the plus 1, and the minus 1,
so there's no higher order.

00:52:58.833 --> 00:53:00.500
What happened to the
rest of the energy?

00:53:03.770 --> 00:53:06.273
STUDENT: Is it absorbed
depending on the grating?

00:53:06.273 --> 00:53:07.690
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right.

00:53:07.690 --> 00:53:11.510
The rest of them got absorbed
or actually reflected

00:53:11.510 --> 00:53:15.690
backwards by the opaque
parts of the grating.

00:53:15.690 --> 00:53:17.510
So remember, this is
an amplitude grating.

00:53:17.510 --> 00:53:19.280
It blocks part of the light.

00:53:19.280 --> 00:53:22.297
So in this case, it's
actually blocked about 50%

00:53:22.297 --> 00:53:22.880
of the energy.

00:53:35.790 --> 00:53:36.970
So as the last example--

00:53:36.970 --> 00:53:41.650
which I will not derive here,
but I will let you go over

00:53:41.650 --> 00:53:43.650
it yourselves at home--

00:53:43.650 --> 00:53:45.420
I did the case of a binary now.

00:53:45.420 --> 00:53:49.740
So this is a phase grating very
similar to the surface relief

00:53:49.740 --> 00:53:52.000
that I showed before,
but in this case,

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:54.090
the phase is a binary function.

00:53:54.090 --> 00:53:55.270
So why is it binary?

00:53:55.270 --> 00:53:58.035
Because this a grating
which is either--

00:54:00.935 --> 00:54:05.140
the light goes either through
a tall part or a short part.

00:54:05.140 --> 00:54:07.800
The tall part, of course,
suffers more phase delay

00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:10.890
because the light has to go
through glass for a little bit

00:54:10.890 --> 00:54:13.080
longer than the short part.

00:54:13.080 --> 00:54:16.680
Therefore, if I plot the phase
of the complex transmission,

00:54:16.680 --> 00:54:18.320
expect to see
something like this.

00:54:18.320 --> 00:54:21.540
The part of the grating that are
taller, they give me a longer

00:54:21.540 --> 00:54:24.930
phase delay, and of course, the
phase delay can now be tried

00:54:24.930 --> 00:54:29.020
normalized so that it is
0 at some reference value.

00:54:29.020 --> 00:54:35.340
And then what is the phase
delay at the long part

00:54:35.340 --> 00:54:39.635
actually depends on the
height of this groove.

00:54:39.635 --> 00:54:41.010
So even the height
of this groove

00:54:41.010 --> 00:54:53.860
is such that s equals
2 pi n minus 1 over--

00:55:01.380 --> 00:55:03.150
let me get this straight.

00:55:03.150 --> 00:55:12.430
So delta phi equals 2
pi upon lambda times

00:55:12.430 --> 00:55:31.980
n times s minus 2 pi over lambda
times s2, where this is s1.

00:55:31.980 --> 00:55:34.740
This is s2.

00:55:34.740 --> 00:55:42.480
So if I say that s1 equals s2
plus s, then what I will get

00:55:42.480 --> 00:55:48.600
is 2 pi over lambda
times n minus 1 times s.

00:55:48.600 --> 00:55:50.250
So you can see from here that--

00:56:04.260 --> 00:56:08.730
so if s is given by lambda
divided by twice the index

00:56:08.730 --> 00:56:12.210
difference between the glass
and the surrounding medium,

00:56:12.210 --> 00:56:18.870
then the phase delay implemented
by this grating is actually pi.

00:56:18.870 --> 00:56:20.430
So if you have a
function like this,

00:56:20.430 --> 00:56:25.570
then, phase delay pi means
that the complex amplitude

00:56:25.570 --> 00:56:30.100
transmission is minus
1, and phase delay 0

00:56:30.100 --> 00:56:31.670
means that it is plus 1.

00:56:31.670 --> 00:56:34.510
So there's is another way
to write this function.

00:56:34.510 --> 00:56:39.305
It is 1 at half of the period,
and minus 1 the other half

00:56:39.305 --> 00:56:40.360
of the period.

00:56:40.360 --> 00:56:42.620
So you can actually--

00:56:42.620 --> 00:56:44.530
it's a little bit of a
[? grind. ?] Next time

00:56:44.530 --> 00:56:46.600
I will show you a
faster way to derive it

00:56:46.600 --> 00:56:52.000
that you can derive the
Fourier series for this kind

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:55.685
of a binary phase grating,
and you'll find actually

00:56:55.685 --> 00:56:56.810
something very interesting.

00:56:56.810 --> 00:56:59.650
I don't know if you noticed
the animation when I showed it.

00:56:59.650 --> 00:57:01.090
Let me play it once again.

00:57:01.090 --> 00:57:07.870
You'll find that even orders
of this grating are actually 0,

00:57:07.870 --> 00:57:10.360
and next time, I will
actually say a little bit more

00:57:10.360 --> 00:57:12.910
about this.

00:57:12.910 --> 00:57:17.230
Anyway, you find the expression
for the diffracted orders

00:57:17.230 --> 00:57:21.850
equals to something that looks
like sine of 5 times the order.

00:57:21.850 --> 00:57:27.070
So of course, if the order is
integral, if the order is even,

00:57:27.070 --> 00:57:29.750
then there's no diffraction.

00:57:29.750 --> 00:57:31.360
It turns out that
this grating has

00:57:31.360 --> 00:57:35.080
a relatively strong diffraction
efficiency of about 40%

00:57:35.080 --> 00:57:37.090
into the first order.

00:57:37.090 --> 00:57:38.950
STUDENT: I've got a question.

00:57:38.950 --> 00:57:40.540
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yes?

00:57:40.540 --> 00:57:42.100
STUDENT: How does
the polarization

00:57:42.100 --> 00:57:44.800
of the incident plane wave
change the diffraction

00:57:44.800 --> 00:57:46.260
efficiencies?

00:57:46.260 --> 00:57:48.260
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: So
these guys were actually

00:57:48.260 --> 00:57:50.660
in the scalar optics
approximation,

00:57:50.660 --> 00:57:55.190
so we neglect the
effect of polarization.

00:57:55.190 --> 00:57:57.770
To include it is actually
rather complicated business

00:57:57.770 --> 00:58:02.150
that we may get to near
the end of this class,

00:58:02.150 --> 00:58:07.580
but it requires something called
coupled wave theory, which

00:58:07.580 --> 00:58:11.000
is relatively advanced.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:14.360
A rule is that if that
period is relatively long,

00:58:14.360 --> 00:58:16.820
a rule of thumb
about 10 wavelengths

00:58:16.820 --> 00:58:20.380
or longer, the effect of
the polarization is minor.

00:58:20.380 --> 00:58:23.900
You have a grating whose
period is 2 wavelengths,

00:58:23.900 --> 00:58:25.713
3 wavelengths,
something like that,

00:58:25.713 --> 00:58:27.380
then the effect is
actually significant,

00:58:27.380 --> 00:58:29.420
and it cannot be neglected.

00:58:29.420 --> 00:58:31.280
But in this class,
we will actually--

00:58:31.280 --> 00:58:32.780
at least at the
beginning, we will

00:58:32.780 --> 00:58:35.630
pretend that the
period is large enough

00:58:35.630 --> 00:58:38.035
that we can neglect
polarization effects.

00:58:38.035 --> 00:58:39.050
Very good question.

00:58:39.050 --> 00:58:41.128
Practice actually
makes a big difference.

00:58:44.800 --> 00:58:45.880
Other questions?

00:58:52.750 --> 00:58:55.850
STUDENT: Just now, we show
one grating, which modifies

